## Using a mutable value as a default value

::: {#95f1053e .cell ExecuteTime='{"end_time":"2021-01-15T08:40:51.446805Z","start_time":"2021-01-15T08:40:51.441178Z"}' execution_count=290}
``` {.python .cell-code}
def foo(bar=[]):
    bar.append('oops')
    return bar

print(foo())
print(foo())
print(foo())

print('-' * 8)
print(foo(['Ah ah']))
print(foo([]))
```
:::


::: {#a7f525a3 .cell execution_count=291}
``` {.python .cell-code}
print(foo.__defaults__)
foo()
print(foo.__defaults__)
```
:::


- The default value for a function argument is evaluated once, when the function is defined
- `the` bar argument is initialized to its default (i.e., an empty list) only when foo() is first defined
- successive calls to `foo()` (with no a `bar` argument specified) use the same list!

One should use instead

::: {#0d33b1e8 .cell ExecuteTime='{"end_time":"2021-01-15T08:40:52.916162Z","start_time":"2021-01-15T08:40:52.908617Z"}' slideshow='{"slide_type":"-"}' execution_count=292}
``` {.python .cell-code}
def foo(bar=None):
    if bar is None:
        bar = []
    bar.append('oops')
    return bar

print(foo())
print(foo())
print(foo())
print(foo(['OK']))
```
:::


::: {#0b0113ce .cell execution_count=293}
``` {.python .cell-code}
print(foo.__defaults__)
foo()
print(foo.__defaults__)
```
:::


No problem with immutable types

::: {#c231568a .cell ExecuteTime='{"end_time":"2021-01-15T08:40:53.337268Z","start_time":"2021-01-15T08:40:53.330411Z"}' execution_count=294}
``` {.python .cell-code}
def foo(bar=()):
    bar += ('oops',)
    return bar

print(foo())
print(foo())
print(foo())
```
:::


::: {#f722b74e .cell execution_count=295}
``` {.python .cell-code}
print(foo.__defaults__)
```
